<article>
    <h1>$40k mo&#xAD;bile app keeps track of bod&#xAD;ies</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201115/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-15"><time>2020-11-15</time></a>
        - <span>SINGAPORE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Calvin Yang</span>
    </section>

    <p>Har­mony Fu­neral Care founder Har­mony Tee spent over $40,000 to de­velop an ap­pli­ca­tion to en­sure that a body mixup like the one last De­cem­ber does not hap­pen again.</p>
    <p>Since June, her firm has re­lied on the app to track about 50 bod­ies – from col­lec­tion and em­balm­ing, to ar­rival at wake venues and their even­tual cre­ma­tion.</p>
    <p>One key fea­ture is the unique QR code gen­er­ated for each de­ceased. The QR code, which cap­tures the per­son’s in­for­ma­tion, is printed and at­tached onto two tear-re­sis­tant iden­ti­fi­ca­tion tags se­cured to the wrist and an­kle of the body.</p>
    <p>The tags in­clude the firm’s logo and the de­ceased’s name so as to re­duce the pos­si­bil­ity of mix-ups, par­tic­u­larly in the em­balm­ing room, where dif­fer­ent bod­ies may be han­dled by dif­fer­ent com­pa­nies.</p>
    <p>Once the em­balm­ing is done, a staff as­signed to col­lect a par­tic­u­lar body will scan the QR code be­fore send­ing it to the wake. If the in­cor­rect QR code is scanned, an er­ror mes­sage ap­pears on the screen and man­age­ment is no­ti­fied. The staff also has to col­lect the body within a stip­u­lated time­frame.</p>
    <p>Fam­i­lies can re­ceive e-mail or SMS no­ti­fi­ca­tions when their loved one is sent from the place of death to the em­balm­ing fa­cil­ity, and when the body is en route to the wake. They can track its progress as tim­ings are given for each stage.</p>


